# 1. Dogs sleep
Hundar sofa.
Hund-ar sofa.

# 2. Dogs chase cars
Hundar elta bíla.
Hund-ar elta bíl-a.

# 3. They chase them.
Þeir elta þá.
Þeir elta þá.

NOTE: There are three genders (neuter plural is used for mixed-gender groups). So there are actually 3 x 3 ways of translating sentence #3. The one above fits the dogs & cars context, since those nouns both happen to be masculine (as does "cat"). Here are the other 8 combos:
Þeir elta þær.
Þeir elta þau.
Þær elta þá.
Þær elta þær.
Þær elta þau.
Þau elta þá.
Þau elta þær.
Þau elta þau.

# 4. These dogs sleep.
Þessir hundar sofa.
Þessir hund-ar sofa.


# 5. Dogs eat.
Hundar éta.
Hund-ar éta.

# 6. I can eat glass.
Ég get borðað gler.
Ég get borð-að gler.

(Ég get étið gler.)
NOTE: There are two verbs for eat (somewhat like German "essen" vs. "fressen"). The "borða" one is used for human subjects, the "éta" one for non-human (i.e. animal) subjects -- but can also colloquially/informally/metaphorically be used with human subjects, so that's why I'm including it in parentheses here.

# 7. It doesn't hurt me.
Mér verður ekki illt af því.
NOTE: The translation of this sentence is heavily context-dependent; I'm taking it to be a continuation of the "I can eat glass" statement. Literally, #7 is something like "Me becomes not hurting/sore from it"

# 8. The dogs chase cars.
Hundarnir elta bíla.
Hund-ar-nir elta bíl-a.

# 9. I think that you know that dogs chase cars.
Ég held að þú vitir að hundar elta bíla.
Ég held að þú vit-ir að hund-ar elta bíl-a.

# 10. I ask whether you know that dogs chase cars.
Ég spyr hvort þú vit-ir að hund-ar elta bíl-a.

# 11. Cats and dogs chase cars.
Kett-ir og hund-ar elta bíl-a.

# 12. Dogs chase cars and cats chase dogs.
Hund-ar elta bíl-a og kett-ir elta hund-a.

# 13. Cats chase dogs and sleep.
Kett-ir elta hund-a og sofa.

# 14. Do cats chase dogs?
elta kett-ir hund-a?

# 15. Chase the dog!
Elt-u hund-inn!

# 16. Hungry dogs eat.
Svang-ir hund-ar éta.

# 17. Hungry dogs eat quickly.
Svang-ir hund-ar éta hratt.
